    "content": "1st: B — 2nd: C — 3rd: A — Reason: Option B (Foreword + Translator's Preface) is ideal. A Foreword by an outside scholar lends credibility and situates the work within broader philosophical discourse for an English-speaking audience unfamiliar with the author — this is especially important for a debut philosophical work in translation. The Translator's Preface remains indispensable: it is where we lay out our translation conventions (the 德 virtue/character split, 现象X as \"phenomenal X,\" the 形而上 reinterpretation, rendering choices for 仁/义/礼, etc.), explain editorial decisions, and orient the reader to the apparatus of footnotes and translator's notes. These are two distinct functions — external endorsement vs. methodological transparency — and mixing them into a single piece would dilute both. Option C (Translator's Preface only) is a solid fallback if no suitable foreword author is available; the translation apparatus is non-negotiable for a work this terminologically dense. Option A (Foreword only) is least preferred because omitting the Translator's Preface would leave the reader without guidance on our systematic rendering choices, which are philosophically consequential."
